{"add":{"doc":{"id":"c8f9950a745102593d414b65bad7071bf1f60efbae03b019e42ed7921ca5e7f5","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Flag_of_CARICOM.svg/220px-Flag_of_CARICOM.svg.png","previous":[],"after":["Caribbean societies are very different from other Western societies in terms of size, culture, and degree of mobility of their citizens.[40] The current economic and political problems the states face individually are common to all Caribbean states. Regional development has contributed to attempts to subdue current problems and avoid projected problems. From a political and economic perspective, regionalism serves to make Caribbean states active participants in current international affairs through collective coalitions. In 1973, the first political regionalism in the Caribbean Basin was created by advances of the English-speaking Caribbean nations through the institution known as the Caribbean Common Market and Community (CARICOM)[41] which is located in Guyana."]}}}